  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "The evolution of anti-money laundering (AML) legislation has been a complex and multi-layered process:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, USA) - First major legislation\n- Focused on requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Limited initial scope and enforcement mechanisms\n\n2. International Developments\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed global standards and recommendations for combating money laundering\n- Created comprehensive international framework for AML regulations\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Expanded AML requirements\n- Enhanced information sharing between agencies\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Modern Legislative Trends\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Increased digital transaction monitoring\n- Broader coverage of financial institutions and sectors\n\n5. Emerging Focus Areas\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Blockchain transaction tracking\n- Cross-border collaboration\n- Advanced technological monitoring systems\n\n6. Recent Developments\n- Enhanced transparency requirements\n- Beneficial ownership disclosure\n- More comprehensive risk-based approaches\n- Significant penalties for non-compliance\n\nThe legislation continues evolving to address emerging financial crime techniques.",
